The first date is the most impressionable date. What better way to do that than learning about your HIV/AIDS status. So, let’s go on a prevention date for World AIDS Day! #worldaidsday2022 (sponsored)

@positiveassistance nurtured such a friendly and safe environnement for screening. Not only that, screening is low cost and offered in your first language. With confidentiality in mind, they made my date and I feel so comfortable despite how anxious we were. 

Thanks to initiatives by the Florida Department of Health like @talktesttreatcfl, I can confidently date knowing my status and have fun!

Overall, I am comfortable in how I look despite critics and unrealistic expectations about my appearance. Being a bad bi*ch never been the issue, it’s your opinions that are.

Reflections from my last day in my twenties ✨ I woke up with deep thoughts of my last day in my 20’s. Looking back, there are so many things I wish I could differently in that decade. But, I say that without regrets. 5 lessons from my 20’s:
•  You are solely responsibile for where you are in life right now. It’s no one else’s doing but your own. There are those put in your life to raise you until it was time you took over. From that point on, it became your responsibility.
• Don’t buy things you don’t need. Literally everything you bought with the desire to impress people, doesn’t even matter.
• Stop trying to be good at everything and find that one thing that’s yours. Your specialty! The one thing people know you for.
• Your existence is important. Yes you’ve lost people but, that doesn’t mean you are lost. Keep living because it’s something you are still blessed with.
• If you don’t see a future with them, don’t bother being in a relationship with them. You’ll save yourself time by listening to that instinct.

Cheers to 30 🥂 (my birthday is tomorrow)

Today marks the first day of my next decade. A decade I pray over serenity, joy, wealth, love, good health, and abundance. Be good to me, 30 🥂 ✨  shot by 📸: @kaneshajanelphoto

Romanticizing Haiti 🇭🇹 

“Change the dial of that radio station from violence and guns in Port-Au-Prince and turn it to the sound of oceans, a robust nightlife, and a welcoming city called Okap. “

Truth is, I am a romantic. Truth is, I am a romantic. Regardless of circumstances, what I imagine, what I want, there is some positive light that Haiti has offer. People constantly diminish its value and undermine its beauty outside of what bad people do. But, Haiti HAS good people. And those good people keep the country running for there to be some support of livelihood. People forget that there are people who live here and actually do what they can to enjoy their lives. It has it quirks and it’s issues (what country doesn’t), but’s it home to SO MANY people. Change the dial of that radio station from violence and guns in Port-Au-Prince and turn it to the sound of oceans, a robust nightlife, and a welcoming city called Okap.  You might actually find the magic in Haiti once you do.

Digital Journal Entry #2 | In my 20s, I had to coast through my journey of self-discovery due to the pressure of growing up so fast.

In my 29th year, I started to shift. It was then that I began to trust the seeds I planted. I began acknowledging my accomplishments, establishing short-term and long-term goals, and closing chapters that seemed endless. Now, 30-year old me feels like she’s validated her 20-year old self and choosing that her best, is enough. But she’s removed the veil that covered and hid parts of her she feared others wouldn’t understand. As I shared my fears about 30 with my 30-plus friends, they all seemed to say the same thing, "you'll love it here" or "you'll start to embrace the changes instead of being afraid of them." Almost a month into my 30's, and I am in love with the woman I'm becoming. 

#personaldevelopment #selfdiscoveryjourney #blackwomanpodcaster
